Teagan Air
It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours.
Teagan Air
If I had to explain to you what it's like to fly in a small plane, I would say it's a mix between riding a motorcycle/ATV and a boat 4,000 feet up in the air.
On the ground you are immediately very fast. It's all a bit unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know yet: You steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the yoke. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
It's wobbly in the air and you're floating a bit. It feels like you're in a boat on the water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you off course, so you practically have to get used to the sea churn, only it's in the air.
One more random detail:
Flying is physically exhausting. Today, my back and my legs ache, as if I had been to the gym.
That's not like a Sunday outing by car. It's rather a sport than a leisurely drive, as I see it now.
A beautiful Saturday, my loved ones. Welcome at 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'm going back there. Then we'll practice airflow break and slow flying.
Today the weather was turbulent, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flight and stall gradually. At one point we had a ground speed of only 16 mph with an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit hazy higher up, but still beautiful.
